<!-- Digestive Enzymes Modal -->
<div id="enzymesModal" class="reveal-modal medium" data-reveal>
  <h2>Digestive Enzymes</h2>

  <p>Within the gastrointestinal tract are enzymes which help to break down proteins and other biological macromolecules. Each enzyme is specific for cleaving (or breaking) a particular chemical bond. Two in particular, trypsin and chymotrypsin, cleave the peptide bonds in proteins. When the peptide bond is cleaved, the C=O side becomes a carboxylic acid (an <span id="red">OH</span> is added) and the NH side becomes an amine (an <span id="blue">H</span> is added). This addition of water is known as hydrolysis.</p>

  <%= image_tag("digestiveEnzyme.png") %>


  <p>As a side note (and not required in your learning just yet), trypsin and chymotrypsin cleave only before or after particular amino acids. Chymotrypsin cleaves at the carboxyl (C=O) side of amino acids with an aromatic or large R group, and trypsin cleaves at the carboxyl side of the amino acids lysine (Lys) or arginine (Arg), except when they are followed by proline (Pro).</p>

  <p>You can read more about digestive enzymes in pages 120-121 of Garrett’s “Biochemistry”, and Chapter 6 of Whitney’s “Understanding Nutrition; 13th Edition”, both of which you can find in the resources section.</p>

