  <h2>Kjeldahl Method</h2>

  <p>The Kjeldahl method is an analytical method used to approximate the amount of protein in a food sample. Using three chemical reactions, the nitrogen present in amino acids are converted into a different form of nitrogen, ammonium borate, which can be measured by titration. Using the titration data, it is possible to first determine how much nitrogen is in the sample, and from this, calculate the approximate amount of protein.</p>

  <p>The Kjeldahl method can be performed manually, or using an automated instrument. In either case, the method requires three steps, which are 1. Digestion, 2. Distillation and 3. Titration. In the first step, the food and protein is ‘digested’ using strong acid, which breaks the protein down to free the nitrogen into a salt form. In the second step, distillation, the nitrogen salt is converted into ammonia, a gas with nitrogen in it, and then another type of nitrogen salt. Finally, in the titration step, a titration is carried out whereby a colour change is used to determine the amount of nitrogen. The chemical reactions for the three steps are shown below.</p>

  <%= image_tag("kjeldahlMethod.png") %>

  <p>The Kjeldahl method is used to measure the amount of nitrogen in a sample, rather than say carbon or hydrogen, because nitrogen is not found in other major food components. For example, fats, sugars and fibres contain carbon and hydrogen and oxygen, but not nitrogen. However, there are some vitamins and minor food components that do contain nitrogen (such as Vitamin B3, Niacin), which is why the Kjeldahl method is an approximate, and not an exact protein calculation. Also, some amino acids (such as Lysine) contain a second nitrogen within their R group, which can also throw out protein calculations.</p>

