<!-- Polarity Modal -->
<div id="polarityModal" class="reveal-modal medium" data-reveal>
  <h2>Hydrophilic and Hydrophobic Domains</h2>

  <p>The tertiary structure is the 3D arrangement of the atoms within the protein. It takes into account the conformation of side chains, as well as the alpha-helices and beta-pleated sheets. The way that proteins fold is dependent on the environment that the protein exists in, and the amino acids present within the protein.</p>

  <p>For example, if Protein A exists in a water- or polar environment, then the protein will be structured so that the majority of the hydrophilic amino acids (those which love water) can interact with the water environment. This may place the hydrophilic amino acids mainly on the outside of the protein and hide the hydrophobic (water-hating) amino acids on the inside of the protein. You can view this in the protein visual; Tick the ‘Polarity’ box in the menu, and use your mouse to move the protein. Can you see one colour mainly on the outside of the protein? In a protein visualisation, hydrophilic areas are often shown in red.</p>

  <p>If Protein B exists in a lipid or non-polar environment, then the protein will be structured so that the majority of the hydrophobic amino acids (those which hate water and like oils) can interact with that non-polar environment. This hydrophobic section, or hydrophobic domain, is often shown in blue in a protein visualisation.</p>

  <p>One example of “Protein B” is Aquaporin, a transmembrane protein which sits inside the lipids of a membrane (which are hydrophobic) and allows water (which is hydrophilic) to pass through it. You can see the transmembrane protein, in yellow in the cartoon below. The top of the image is the inside of a cell, and the bottom right of the image is the outside of the cell, with the lipid membrane of the cell shown in light blue.</p>

  <p>Most of the outside of the protein is in contact with the lipid membrane, apart from small sections at the top and bottom of the membrane. Therefore, this outer, middle section of the protein must made up of non-polar, or hydrophobic, amino acids to allow the protein and membrane to interact and hold the protein in place. Meanwhile, the inside of the transmembrane protein must have polar (hydrophilic) amino acids which allows the flow of water through.</p>

  <%= image_tag("polarity1.jpg") %>

  <p>You can see the hydrophilic and hydrophobic sections of the transmembrane protein Aquaporin in the visualisation below. The majority of the outside of the protein is blue (hydrophobic), as the outer of the protein needs to interact with nonpolar membrane lipids. Meanwhile, the inside of the protein is mainly red (hydrophilic), as it must interact with water passing through. The upper and lower sections of the protein are also hydrophilic, as they must sit in polar areas inside and outside of the cells.</p>

  <%= image_tag("polarity2.png") %>

  <p><i>Aquaporin, where <b>A</b> shows the transmembrane area of the protein which interacts with the lipid membrane, and <b>B</b> shows the pore through which water passes across membrane without touching the lipid bilayer.</i></p>

  <p>You can read more about hydrophilic and hydrophobic domains in Chapter 5 (pg 178 and Figure 5.11 on pg 182) of Coultate’s “Food; the Chemistry of its Components”, and Chapter 6 of Whitney’s “Understanding Nutrition; 13th Edition”, both of which you can find in the resources section.</p>

